{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490890"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:20:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:20:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"772"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/772"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.08,0.06,0.16,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/772"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"528"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"592"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33868"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of nausea, vomiting, with the vomitus containing small amounts of fresh blood. The vomiting began after a night of heavy alcohol consumption. He typically drinks about 20 g of alcohol daily but had been on a binge the evening prior to presentation. He has a two-week history of post-prandial epigastric pain for which he recently started taking esomeprazole. He has no other significant medical history and takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly dehydrated. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness but no guarding or rebound tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mallory-Weiss tear","Oesophageal varices","Erosive oesophagitis","Acute gastritis","Duodenal ulcer"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic history for a Mallory-Weiss tear: small volume haematemesis following forceful vomiting after alcohol consumption. \u003Cstrong\u003EMallory-Weiss\u003C/strong\u003E tears are mucosal lacerations that occur at the gastro-oesophageal junction, typically caused by a sudden increase in intra-abdominal pressure during retching or vomiting. The tear results in small volume bleeding that is usually self-limiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal varices\u003C/strong\u003E typically present with more significant, often massive haematemesis rather than the small volume described here. While this patient has a history of alcohol consumption, there is no mention of chronic liver disease or portal hypertension, which would be prerequisites for the development of varices. Variceal bleeding is typically not preceded by vomiting; rather, the haematemesis is often the initial symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErosive oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause haematemesis, but it is usually associated with a longer history of reflux symptoms such as heartburn and regurgitation. While the patient has been started on esomeprazole for epigastric pain, the acute onset of symptoms following alcohol consumption and vomiting is more consistent with a Mallory-Weiss tear than with bleeding from oesophagitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute gastritis\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly alcohol-induced gastritis, can cause epigastric pain and nausea, but significant haematemesis would be unusual. When bleeding does occur from gastritis, it typically presents as coffee-ground emesis or occult bleeding rather than fresh blood after vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuodenal ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E bleeding typically presents with melaena or coffee-ground emesis rather than fresh blood in the vomitus. While the patient\u0027s history of epigastric pain could suggest peptic ulcer disease, the temporal relationship between forceful vomiting and subsequent haematemesis strongly favours a Mallory-Weiss tear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of Mallory-Weiss tears is generally supportive, as most stop bleeding spontaneously. Endoscopy may be required for diagnosis and occasionally for therapeutic intervention if bleeding persists. Risk factors for Mallory-Weiss tears include conditions that increase intra-abdominal pressure such as vomiting, retching, coughing, or straining, with alcohol consumption being a common precipitating factor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mallory-Weiss tears are mucosal lacerations at the gastro-oesophageal junction typically caused by forceful vomiting or retching.","Small volume haematemesis following forceful vomiting is characteristic of Mallory-Weiss tears.","Alcohol consumption is a common precipitating factor for Mallory-Weiss tears."],"references":["Wilkins T, Khan N, Nabh A, Schade RR. Diagnosis and management of upper gastrointestinal bleeding. Am Fam Physician. 2012 Mar 1;85(5):469-76. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/afp/2012/0301/p469.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"772"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81062"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-16T11:17:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-16T11:18:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"772"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98668"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":